Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the liberation of Tymosenko
The Ukrainian parliament refused, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs refused in second reading the proposed amendment to reduce penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded a seemingly disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court must decide on the appeal of the convicted in December.
Tymosenko described the ruling as political revenge of the regime and provoked a process of suspicions of bias of the court also in the west.
The plan to annul paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was sentenced, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
