How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time proposed trips mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the west, however it was necessary to queue all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency agreement that was the condition to travel to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs spent most of their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs were buying and this habit continues until now.
The Czechs' journeys have since 1989 experienced a major revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were to the maximum, the Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million days of holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 as part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the west has led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not for a long time travel by plane to the west, which everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris the travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical trait of a Czech trip was at that time to carry with you his own preserved food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown, which finally allowed our tourists after decades to be able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average wage have increased which has led to another important moment around 1997.
With increasing demand for travel travel travel agencies have begun since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter routes which thanks to contracts have dramatically reduced costs compared to what was before.
By the end of the 90s of the last century the Czechs had visa-free connections with almost most developed countries around the world except the EU which later facilitated our journeys.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when was prepared the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutional development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008 the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time again in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person on holidays abroad including ancillary charges. Crowns per person.
