A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won prizes, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and acts as an exhibition house.
If you are enthusiastic about a modern post-war architecture, its clear shapes, its glass hangars, its lively and bold looks and its new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl schwanzer for the Universal Exhibition in Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example.
