Its project of pavilion as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at the station of the South of Vienna, was transformed, and in 1962 a museum of the 20th century opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the works of art, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for so long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has become more and more unladen.
Now architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name "Maison du 21ème siècle" and will in future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck from any point of view.
The new start was completed by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as an art skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, she carried out particularly the transformation work with politicians and the protection of monuments, she obtained public funds and private sponsorship and established its exploitation.
Except for contemporary art, the works of sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited there, a café and a bookshop are there, and an office has to be built there.
Strict supervision, small budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter.
Not only because he had transformed and sensibly expanded Joseph Ombracht's secession and had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of its move to Vienna and its change of use.
During the current transformations, there were major problems: the building was "an energy abyss," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, glass fibre reinforced insulation glass was laid and the roof replaced by a particular safety glass.
The beams of the thermal bridges have been reinforced or replaced, and the asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a light panel sifted between the house and the road provides the lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it is almost a new construction, but always the light Pavillon Schwanzer.
