Peter Englund's new book offers depth and generosity. Titled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", it begins with a long list of characters that holds your heart together.
A tip to start with: carefully tear this page and make it your page mark.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this romantic narrative by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, who delivers the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book that he accurately describes as "an anti-history book."
It has some well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and materials is found.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it could look like." It includes "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and grief" summarizes the experiences in wartime of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and vendors.
Some will become heroes.
Others of the prisoners of war, some of them will lose limbs, go crazy or lose their lives.
Their lives wander here like the candles of a church: while some of them turn off, new ones are turned on again.
Peter Englund's book departs from traditional history books.
He refuted the idea that World War I was summed up only by the terrible trench war on the western front.
"Beauty and grief" cleverly describes other war theatres: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one passes Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
The war invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks of the cordite.
When gunshots sound in the distance, and you are a mother at home, do you stay or flee?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been compounded by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and grief" follows such individuals as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most address deprivation and the ability to cope.
By telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues on alternative food in Germany.
He describes "meat made of cooked rice crushed in sheep's fat (and finished with a fake wood bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
