7 lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview at the cinema this week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical engineering and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans can find more revealing in a recently discovered Steve Jobs interview that will be aired this week as the first part of a film in the main markets, is how much this creative spirit had understood the processes and workflow of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified himself with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as a flowchart enhancer - a man who believed that many business leaders were suffering from a "disease that they thought a great idea made 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds". This series traces the birth of the computer, and he sits for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, Steve Jobs had had to leave Apple for about 10 years. He was already working hard on his new NeXT computer company, aiming at a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in the transport.
It was only after Steve Jobs died that a full video was found in the director's garage.
This video, slightly up, is the basis of the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be aired at the cinema next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism reappears, when he seems eager to hear the questions of Cringely, giving him elbows to speed it up and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone, one finds a strangely prescient aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision on the future of computing.
It's one thing to read the posthumous reviews of Steve Jobs' career, but there's something crude and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can be and should be.
He explains them and then sets them in motion.
Here is a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences of Lost Interview:
On how he learned how to run a business:
"During all these years, I've always asked, 'Why do you do things?' and the answers are constantly the same: 'oh, just because we have to do them.'"
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues by providing details on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how the costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" evaluated from the nose, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed the precise calculation of the commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a tour of the Pope:
Steve Jobs recounts the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack telephone networks and phone for free in long distance.
The apparatus has been the subject of many writings beforehand, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We wrapped the ball in different things half a dozen times and you were screaming in the public phone and it happened to you a minute later on the public phone next door," says Jobs laughing.
"We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world."
We didn't know much, but we were able to invent a little thing that could control great things. It was an amazing lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by telling a wonderful trick that he and Wozniak developed: he called the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night by pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices leave in a wild laugh just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love for technology (and Bill Hewlett's pitch):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he looked for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and made a phone call to him.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs gets a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company's research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode tube. I fell in love with it.
The teenager I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On Improvisation of Innovation:
At several moments in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a head start.
At the beginning of his career, as he moved in to sell some printed circuit boards, a client asked him to assemble a complete computer.
Working only 30 days of credit, he had to take care of the assembly and delivery of the finished appliances.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big fights... they yelled at me pretending it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that was incredibly reliable.
On the large companies that run out of steam:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs anticipated how many industrial leaders would be mistaken and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [it's these types of people] who end up running companies and the specialized product staff are kept away from decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who cannot imagine designing a good product compared to a bad product - the required manual work.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They tore the defeat out of victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
"A huge piece of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop this idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about his subtleties.
There are compromises to do... some things you can't do, the electrons can, the glass, the robots, the factories too.
You must keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by bringing them together.
Finally, decisions are made out of personal taste. It is about trying to expose you to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring these things to the product you create.
Picasso once said that the good artists are copying and that the great artists are stealing.
We're always ashamed of stealing great ideas.
This is in part what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who were simply the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
