Court validates "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The substitution of analogue signals by digitals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analogous cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been brought together.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to follow in order to realize the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was rejected for failing to reach the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because the regulation of radio and television is a statutory allocation to the Federal Commission of Telecommunications (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favour of the draft voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero has suspended the application of the decree and all the actions provided by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the ministers also rejected the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure the measures for the preparation of the public administration through general standards.
"I also consider that it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, whose constitutional mandate is the direction of the State.
The substitution of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and this translates into better radio spectrum operation, better signal quality and more channels.
To maintain the change, he argued, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalization which implies a decision of public interest that does not only have a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues".
These questions, he stressed, "require the operation of a whole system establishes, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, includes a group of responsibilities which the Constitution grants to the power of the State Executive".
He recalled that a large number of countries from all over the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have the highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, has invaded in a form the sphere of competence of Congress, for it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislative, he asserted.
