Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group made up of the world's stronger emerging and developed countries, and has been in force with the South American country since January this year to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the implementation of tax exchange agreements to get out of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) 'gri list', which is being integrated by countries that do not implement all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
On the trade side, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Treaty (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
