Casino forgives Jonás Larrazábal and this one will be released
After 72 days of provisional arrest, the legal authority of Casino Red granted forgiveness to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey for the trial initiated against him for alleged blackmail
After having spent 72 years arrested, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal will be released after the founder of the legal power of the Casino Red grants him forgiveness before the Second Criminal Court of the District, which follows a trial for blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, Casino Red owner Sergio Gil García published a series of photos and videos in which Manuel Jonás allegedly required him to pay for an economic quotte so that the mayor of Monterrey would allow the underground operation of the gambling house.
After the public denunciation, the Public Prosecutor's Office opened a criminal trial against the brother of the mayor of PANiste and on 2 September he was arrested and held under provisional arrest for 30 days.
After four hours in front of Public Prosecutor's Office Officer 3 of Patrimonial Delitions, he was transferred to Detention Centre 1, located in the Old Quarter of the State Capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days when a second detention order was issued after the Public Prosecutor's Office had dismissed corruption and organized crime offences.
On October 19 he was transferred to the criminal center of Cadereyta allegedly for blackmailing the owners of the Red Casino with one and a half million pesos; but he spent only a few hours in the medium security detention centre because there were death threats against him.
The authorities allowed him to continue the trial in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On 25 October, a catch order was issued by the clerk of the Second District Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigation there was sufficient confirmed evidence to determine Jonás' guilt, such as that relating to the receipt of 1.5 million pesos from the representatives of the gambling house in exchange for its operation.
This Monday, the founder of the legal power of the Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, presented himself before Judge José Luis Pecina to ask forgiveness for the brother of the mayor of the region; therefore he could regain his freedom during the following hours.
During the legal formalities, the public prosecutor's officer attached to the Tribunal, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez if the damage had been recovered and who had been the partner of the gambling house who had granted the pardon, but the lawyer tried not to communicate the name.
According to file 197/2011, Jonás Larrazábal is legally pardoned and no claims can be made about the trial against him; no compensation or punishment will be sought.
After the hearing of the lawyer of the legal power of the gambling house, at 15:50 hours the immediate freedom of Larrazabal Bretón was ordered.
The Registrar of the Court, Jorge Yánez, moved to the prison of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to inform Jonás that he had been pardoned legally and his file would be closed.
He will also inform him of the immediate order of freedom issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives the details of the air accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake and other seven people lost his life
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) informed that the results of the accident in which Secretary of Government Francisco Blake Mora and other seven people lost their lives indicate that the helicopter directly shocked the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, reported that prior to the aircraft's take-off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage".
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so the unit met the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that investigations in the impact area do not report the appearance of ground parts.
"In one search it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact was structural.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The soil had a pant of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For the moment, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as quickly as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that the moment of impact, the State Major Presidential helicopter was operating in cruise speed and this happened on a soft rising ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he says.
During the press conference, the SCT holder, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual theft:
According to aeronautical standards, the flight was conducted according to visual flight rules, which means that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM indicated adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between DF and the State of Mexico, there were layers of low-level nebulosity.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the nebulosity conditions the crew looked for a lower height area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft remains in a reduced area:
The information available to date suggests that the impact has occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The aircraft's residual dispersion model assumes that the helicopter struck the ground under structural integrity conditions.
Traces of fire or explosion have not been detected:
At the accident site there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of any type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had had multiple contact with the ground.
During the fieldwork, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above the average sea level, and the ground had a slope that has been going from seven gradients to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he may have disarticulated himself along his journey.
The information provides evidence that suggests that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful search in a larger area than the surrounding area, around the accident, dispersed parts of the aircraft were not found, which supported the presumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity conditions.
MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene for children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene for children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Obesity of Children and Adolescents' protocol that will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialities of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Investigation and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation it is invited to participate the population who are entitled or not, to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence is made to the minors every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtemoc Sport Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October the activity takes place in the Sport Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sportive Independencia Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sportive Morelos Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that of knowing the components and the importance of genetics in the development of obesity and of identifying risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of the specific questionnaires relating to diet.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, height circumference), blood pressure, glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol, and insulin and genetic levels will be applied to all participants (people associated with childhood obesity are being identified).
Cruz López pointed out that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there was an increase in the proportion of boys in obesity of 77 per cent and in the proportion of girls in 47 per cent; in the case of overweight there was also a dramatic increase', the IMSS specialist pointed out.
He indicated that the rationale for finding markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the others because of its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American heredity, a 30 percent European and a five percent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn excess energy that is consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the participants is the full assessment of children, which makes it possible to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-coloured folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the probability of suffering metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and physicians provide it to parents in writing, explaining each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to take to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarianism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of TV and use means of transport instead of going on foot for short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - meat paté with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better efficiency, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand blackcurrants each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the asphalt pavement is adequate, the blackcurrants could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion on blackcurrants, organized within the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture having characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with a greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the yield, and therefore the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a lower molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behaviour of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineer.
The QF researcher observed that the majority of the streets of Ciudad de México were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three involving asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones forming the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating effort, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, it would spread better, opinated the chemical ingener.
On the asphalt layer, he says, one puts a last layer called a rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the bearing layer also requires that it be of adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil wets, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all layers of the pavement and therefore causes blackcurrants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that spoils itself is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Researcher System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrants and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of blackcurrants.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair blackcurrants easily and without having to use high temperatures.
