So was the work of Cali's person who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A typist from Cali has passed to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
The past November 4 a typist of the CTI of Cali has passed to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme chief of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano", comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists who work in the local offices of the CTI, this week it was the turn of "availability" of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to arrive at the place where the corpses were to be identified.
In 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after attending appropriate courses, he specialized in typoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, i.e. palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano, Eliazar had been warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a Palmira helicopter.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be the man who was running the world's oldest guerrilla, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the dead body, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, as it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But the prints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a pre-elevator and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the Farc.
Looking for the fingerprint
For a typist from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos gave to Eliazar González in a press conference for the operation against "Cano" is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Typing is an exact science, without margin of error, which can be crucial in solving crimes.
Apart from identifying the corpses, typists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false identity cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher testified that in one case of theft he had to remove a part of a wall from a house, because in that place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate areas to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint with all the hand and identify the offender who had participated in various robberies," he recalls.
Fingerprints may also dismiss or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently a dead man was found, with bottles of drink around him.
By investigation, it was determined that a parent may be suspect of the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee that he's the killer, it puts him at the crime scene.
A CTI typist explained that "the fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents" are extracted.
When they appear, a pre-releaser or tape is used to remove them.
Subsequently, the prints are sent to Asif, the database of the declines, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many Colombians without papers," said the expert from the ITC.
He explained that not everything is how we show in the CSI television program.
Like everything that shines is not gold, everything you touch does not necessarily become a fingerprint.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
The "indignant" defy the authorities in New York
Hundreds of protesters were rushing in front of Zuccotti Square to camp there.
A large part of the people accessed the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
The integrations of the Occupe Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities this Tuesday by trying to enter again, thanks to a judicial order, instead of Manhattan, from where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another park of the Great Apple.
Hundreds of protesters were rushing in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a judicial order that allows the 'indignant' to camp again in this place, while the other side of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new stops.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we will settle in another place and we will continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations," says one of the spokespersons of the movement "Occupe Wall Street", Mark Bray.
Bray explained that the response of the 'indignants' to the evacuation of their personally dictated camp by the mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, came to the courts, where Justice Lucy Billings issued an order that prohibited the forced evacuation of the place and allowed the demonstrators to remain in the camp.
In addition, the 'Indignates' occupied a new park located at the confluence of Canal Street power stations and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested a few protesters, even though Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization assures that there are hundred years of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved in support of the members of the movement and tried to intervene in favour of them before the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a private property compound - remains closed pending the celebration of a judicial hearing scheduled for this Tuesday during which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analysed.
Some of the protesters who had been displaced so far were carrying and distributing copies of this judicial order at that time and they even handed it over to the agents who were watching the square, which caused 'some small clashes', Bray said, who denounced the fact that some officials hit the demonstrators.
The judicial order prohibits the authorities from evacuating the members of Occupe Wall Street or from applying 'laws published after the beginning of the occupation or from prohibiting demonstrators from re-entering the park with tents or other properties they used previously'.
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, as a result of this judicial order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and demonstrators, but warned them that local laws did not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The City Councillor personally defended the evacuation carried out at dawn in Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and decided on because of the fact that the demonstrators were 'in violation of the law'.
Bloomberg explained that he had ordered the square to be evacuated because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases to hurt others", because "some shops had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"The evacuation this morning at dawn has been repugnant and shows that deep down Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman of the movement, who accused the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression".
The leaders of "Occupe Wall Street" also indicated that they do not plan to organize "great actions" on Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions to commemorate the two months of protest, which began on 17 September.
