Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP rises a 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March the Japanese economy was paralyzed, recovering again after the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe in the Japanese country since World War II.
The initial estimates of the Tokyo Government calculated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP increased one 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and one 6% in annualized rates.
That recorded in the second quarter - for Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also assumes, in addition, the greatest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the post-tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the decrease of 0.9% of capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decrease after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructure, to use the deficiencies to grow from scratch.
Japan has woken up mainly thanks to the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refusal values" elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in Eurozone and the disturbances predicted by the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of major technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, were responsible for their low performance between July and September for the yen's contribution.
While markets continue to have their seats in the outlying EU countries, the Yoshihiko Noda Government does not decline guard.
"We must monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
And indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) mentioned that the majority of member countries presented clearer signals of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are being restrained.
Because it has dropped four decimals to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone has even been below the average, which is in level 100, falling eight decimals to 99.13 points.
