The first day of the congress of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), Monday 14 November, in Leipzig, was without real difficulty for Angela Merkel, Chancellor but also President of the Christian Democratic Party.
The future of Europe was not originally foreseen in the programme but was imposed in the autumn, in particular to satisfy the activists who consider the policy of the government too lax vis-à-vis the Greeks today and perhaps the Italians tomorrow.
The motion on the Presidency of the European Commission, proposed by management, was adopted almost unanimously.
Out of 1001 delegates, only nine voted against and ten abstained.
The standing ovation of several minutes to which, at the end of their interventions, Angela Merkel and, a few hours later, Wolfgang Schäuble, the very europhile finance minister, did not give way to doubt.
The Chancellor's - and the motion's - idea is based on a slogan: the response to the crisis "is not less of Europe but more of Europe".
Not only because Europe is peace, but because "nine million jobs are directly dependent on the euro".
For the Chancellor, "the time has come for a breakthrough in Europe".
This could lead to amendments to the Treaty of Lisbon to strengthen the European Union's control over the budgetary policies of the euro area countries, but it could also lead to the election of the President of the European Commission by universal suffrage "in order to give a face to Europe".
