What does sickness arrest fraud mean?
After the allowances, the UMP and the government launch the offensive on sick stoppages.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be in Bordeaux on Tuesday 15 November to visit a family allowance fund, and deliver a speech on the theme - recurring since 2007 - of the fight against social fraud and assistance.
And to accompany this offensive, which starts from a desire to make savings in a context of rigour, but is no less heralding an axis of the presidential campaign to the right, the majority wants to focus on sick stops.
First of all, with a view to budgetary savings: the government plans to impose a fourth day's waiting period on employees of the private sector before taking care of a stoppage of work.
In short, without a specific company agreement, an employee who becomes ill would lose four days' pay, thus at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that could provoke anger, but would yield 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
This would be accompanied by another, more symbolic measure: to impose a day of unremunerated deficiency on civil servants in the event of a stoppage of work (until now they have no waiting period, compared with three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority is also reviving the issue of fraud, this time targeting abuses related to work stoppages.
"The controls will be much more important and, if you are taken, you will pay back," warned Xavier Bertrand at RTL's microphone on Sunday 13 November.
As in other cases, the publicity effects seem somewhat disproportionate to the reality of work stoppage fraud.
Since 2002, this has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives, which have mostly borne fruit.
The French are not sicker than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us focus first on the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than 237 million euros of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, in 2008 daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditure, with 11.3 billion euros.
Of this sum, 46% concerned maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% concerned sick leave, i.e. EUR 6.2 billion.
And thus 2.5% of health spending.
In 2010, the French had an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 days in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
An average that hides some discrepancies: another survey, published in 2007 by the career management site Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken any sick days.
Another study, this time of Sickness Insurance, states that in 2010, 37% of sick leave was of a duration of less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more inclined than elsewhere to stop work.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) varied between 10% and 11% in France, compared with 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud at sick stoppages represents very little in the face of work in the dark.
As for fraud, it is only a small scale.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 means that checks are systematic on sick leave for more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million checks, CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 short-term stops were "unjustified or too long", or 37,050 cases.
In the case of stops of more than 45 days, systematically checked, there were 11% "unsuitable or unjustified" cases out of 1.2 million, or 132 000.
In total, 169,000 "unjustified" cases out of several million employees who had a sick stoppage.
A figure which represents very little, for example, of work in the dark.
According to MP UMP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the matter in June, the latter would amount to 9 to 15 billion euros of tax loss per year, more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud against them.
