Recall that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid poll conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of elderly or disabled people are less valuable.
As for those who have performed assisted suicide, respondents estimate that they should not be prosecuted at 41%.
In terms of patient retention or cessation of care, the situation is less clear, says the report authors.
Therefore, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it should be stated in the Criminal Code that withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Committee of Experts also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect a denial of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In terms of palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care, beyond cancer cases.
Finally, with respect to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee asks that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations by other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada's expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described the position of the experts who signed the report as "extreme", among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation where everyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 years old could ask for help to commit suicide," said Mr Deschamps, who yesterday had consulted a summary of the report.
Mr. Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the individual's autonomy above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
"In society," he says, "there are beacons and constraints."
Health Law Specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she called a "pro-euthanasia demonstration".
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, disputes in particular the report's data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, in the Netherlands and Oregon.
