Energy policy:
facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is one subject which cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is indeed energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is healthy that an election meeting should be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear power there.
The debate will be fruitful only if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While there are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of demand for electricity by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be overcome in order to continue to produce electricity permanently, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case with Belgium, which is subjecting its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor with Switzerland, which just intends to build only last generation power plants.
On the other hand, the Czech Republic, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States, after Fukushima, decided to add a unit to its park by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
While the German model, which focuses on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality upsets discourse.
Berlin's choice will result in higher electricity prices, an increase in energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, particularly from Russia, a surge in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to be considered.
He is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind, from which he draws 30% of his electricity, so that his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are 65% and 50% higher respectively than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than those of French households.
Whereas in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the least expensive electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would result in a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the fine declarations on the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
A price which a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show.
Let us recall that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Highly exportative, it leads to a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and makes them very creative of non-localizable jobs.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the annual €6 billion worth of French exports of nuclear equipment and services as a source of grief.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to operate for sixty years when the decline of its manufacturer would be scheduled?
In order to solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miracle electricity generation, no more than there is a diabolical one.
The development by Areva of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
We have in France a Safety Authority which exercises intransigent and transparent control over existing power plants as well as on the Flamanville yard.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession of safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident results from two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that have caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between safety authorities, operators and manufacturers in France and Germany, the EPR presents a design that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians who want to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a wonderful gift to the competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them the way to seize the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to leave emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers to dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the number, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "human rights countries" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has come to light, the Minister of the Interior (read Libération of 23 May) proclaiming that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus on this issue between the left and the right.
To the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million migrant workers", and to the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared to the left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may pay electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and impairs employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are likely to replace national workers, especially low-skilled workers, who are putting downward pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mostly in occupations in sectors in need of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country where there is a shortage of anesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has thus calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows results in an increase between 0.6 and 0.9% of real wages in the long term.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the U.S. Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average up to 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of EUR 150000 to public budgets on average over his entire life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to look for the missing growth points "with teeth".
The teeth in question, when used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be enough for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies to vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was an easy thought.
Universal suffrage, in order to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression" as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much, and first and foremost a crisis of politics and democracy.
In this respect, the palinodia of the true-false Greek referendum has had the value of double revealing: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought of in order to be exceeded.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now moved, and that, for many of them, Republican soldiers no longer shoot in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized as necessary and in a dispersed order.
A blanc-seing with the absolute European monarch or a joint jump in the vacuum of nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts, but a common exercise, of full right, serene and continuous, of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - there is no more way to stop enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that bends to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole that slowly loses its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
It is together that Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The end of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After long fighting this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today calls for the European economic government.
Fine.
But thinking this without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by the citizens, would be a new folly and a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "do" republicans.
The Revolution in Interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more democratic Europe politically, a true European popular sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
