The Nord Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe and Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new pipeline that directly connects Russia under the sea with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his counterpart in the Netherlands Mark Rutte have together turned the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first tube of 1,224 km linking the St Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is due to be completed by the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we already talk about the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and hour of this huge construction site looks like a victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any overland passage by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream with a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is to say, the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas-consuming and whose deposits are in decline.
"This gas pipeline is a part of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon by inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by Gazprom's leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-coated steel to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average distance of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be abducted or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
There was also a need for more measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project authorities abandoned it while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company permanently set up off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have planned the welds to leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the condition of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for outdoor observation, as well as by an aircraft that is circulating inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter wide, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, he gives precise information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars on departure, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture, named Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its seat in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to the company, for 20 renewable years, all the gas transmission capacity.
"Gasprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to get in their way, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 metres high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the coming gas before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskin, a brand book.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskin wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskin notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a off-white color, as aged by time.
Yet, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design but distinguished notes.
Maria Sebregondi, then consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is based on an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travellers.
" Moleskin has restored to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the XXth century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces.
We are far from the confidential production of the first few years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskin crossed Italian borders and exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw up a sketch portrait of the buyer, as the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, has almost 100 today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city centre and has been able to impose her identity.
"We followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a range of supports.
A success that made envious: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the SG Capital Europe investment fund, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the population as a whole.
Disconcerting?
"No," said Eric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled."
" The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that for the disabled unemployed, there are still many obstacles to access to employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a diploma and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, all these criteria, which make it particularly difficult to return to employment, and which "are the crux of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for the objective brakes.
The unspoken attitude remains, the attitudes that are changing, certainly, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of the disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychically or intellectually impaired".
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The latest figures from 2008 show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," said Pierre Blanc, managing director of the Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 (from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
